text.text: If you already have a health savings account (HSA), you can sign up for a limited-purpose flexible spending account to help pay for eligible dental and vision expenses with tax-free dollars. By having a limited-purpose flexible spending account, you get to save your HSA dollars for other expenses.

accordionItem0.title: What a limited-purpose FSA pays for

text.text: Here is a list of some of the eligible dental and vision expenses that you can pay for with a limited-purpose FSA. For a full list of expenses and rules, visit irs.gov.

Dental

  • Artificial teeth
  • Braces
  • Dental services such as exams, cleanings, fillings, and X-rays
  • Dental plan deductible, coinsurance and copayments
  • Mouth guards
  • Health plan deductible, coinsurance and copayments —if dental services are covered
  • Orthodontia services
  • Tooth caps and tooth removals

Vision

  • Contact lenses and solutions
  • Eyeglasses and frames
  • Health plan deductible, coinsurance and/or copayments —if vision services are covered
  • LASIK eye surgery
  • Vision exams
  • Vision plan deductible, coinsurance and copayments
Sign up for a dependent care flexible spending account (FSA) to pay for eligible day care and elder care expenses with tax-free dollars.

accordionItem0.title: What a dependent care FSA pays for

text.text: Here is a list of some of the eligible dental and vision expenses that you can pay for with a limited-purpose FSA. For a full list of expenses and rules, visit irs.gov.

Child care expenses

  • Before and after school care and extended care programs for dependents under age 13
  • Babysitter — who is not your child, under age 19 and a tax dependent
  • Child care and qualified child care centers for dependents under age 13
  • Nursery school
  • Preschool

Elder care expenses

  • Adult day care center for dependents age 13 or older who are not able to support themselves
  • Elder care while you work (in your home or someone else’s)
  • Senior day care
Sign up for a health care flexible spending account (FSA) to pay for eligible health care expenses with tax-free dollars.

accordionItem0.title: What a health care FSA pays for

text.text: When you sign up for the commuter expense reimbursement account, you can keep more of your money because you don't pay taxes on the money you set aside for eligible commuting and parking expenses.

accordionItem0.title: What a commuter expense reimbursement account pays for

text.text:
Use the account to pay for the following services:

  • Public transit services such as bus, light rail, regional rail, streetcar, trolley, subway or ferry
  • Vanpool
  • Parking at or near work
  • Parking at or near public transportation for your commute
